  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States and internationally:\n\n1. U.S. Federal Laws:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. State Laws:\n- Many states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws\n\n3. International Frameworks:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n\nThese statutes typically:\n- Define money laundering\n- Establish reporting requirements\n- Mandate customer due diligence\n- Create penalties for violations\n- Require financial institutions to implement compliance programs\n- Provide mechanisms for investigating and prosecuting money laundering activities\n\nThe primary goals of these statutes are to:\n- Prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds\n- Detect and deter financial crimes\n- Promote transparency in financial transactions\n- Protect the integrity of financial systems\n\nPenalties can include significant fines and potential imprisonment for individuals and organizations found guilty of money laundering.",
